Basal area increment models accounting for climate and mixture for Austrian tree species

Abstract

Forest trees exhibit a large variation in basal area increment, which depends on tree specific factors, inter-tree relations and the environment. Studying the effect of the above factors on tree growth is essential for forest ecology and forest management. In this study, a basal area increment model for 22 tree species of the Austrian National Forest Inventory was parameterized. The model included effects of tree size, competition, harvesting and disturbances, climate, soil, and species mixtures. The models were fitted using generalized additive models. Basal area increment increased with tree size for all species, and competition and density reduced tree growth. Shade-tolerant tree species showed a more pronounced decrease with competition, than light-demanding tree species. Tree growth increased with disturbance intensity, but confidence intervals for high disturbance intensities became larger. Many variants of the model that included climatic effects were tested, but the best variants used long-term-mean temperature and precipitation during the growing season and the positive and negative deviations thereof, which separated climatic site effects from temperature deviations due to yearly weather conditions. Several of the tested dryness indices were not able to explain tree growth from inventory data. Soil type and soil moisture were significant for many tree species, each of them accounting for a maximum of 10% of difference in tree growth. Little growth was observed on calcareous Leptosols, whereas trees grew best on Planosols, on flysch or calcareous Cambisols. Growth was decreased on dry sites, but very moist and wet sites could result in either a decrease or an increase in growth, depending on the tree species. Mixture effects were significant for almost all mixtures with a sufficient number of observations in the data set. Notable exceptions were the mixtures of Pinus sylvestris L. with Picea abies (L.) Karst. and Abies alba Mill. and the mixtures of Quercus spp. with Pinus sylvestris L. and Fagus sylvatica L.. Mixture effects were both favorable and adverse at individual tree level. Picea abies and Fagus sylvatica were two tree species, which were mainly favored by mixture effects. Interactions of mixture with age or site could not be modelled from the data because they were confounded with other effects of the inventory data. The new basal area increment model provided a comprehensive formulation, which can be use part of individual tree growth simulators and is easily transferable to other regions and environments and can be extended in the future.

1. Introduction

Forest trees exhibit a large variation in basal area growth rate, which depends on tree specific factors, inter-tree relations and the environment. Well known and demonstrated by many studies is the increase of basal area increment with tree size or age (Stephenson et al., 2014). As trees grow, they are able to support more foliage, which in turn results in increased photosynthesis and carbon storage. For tree sizes usually found in forest inventories this increase is continuous (e.g. Monserud and Sterba, 1996). There is some discussion, however, if this increase in growth levels of for very old trees. Recent research, however, shows that at the individual tree level the continuous increase persists, at least in terms of carbon storage (Stephenson et al., 2014). Tree growth rates are species specific and the species specific response to the environment is also a major driver for large scale patterns of species presences and absence, because of competitive advantages and disadvantages of different tree species (Bueckling et al., 2017).

Competition is a key constraint to tree growth, which limits individual tree resources above and below-ground. The importance of competition for tree growth is well recognized and has been demonstrated in many studies (Biging and Dobbertin, 1992, Biging and Dobbertin, 1995, Weiskittel et al., 2011). Many different measures for competition or stand density have been proposed and indices are so numerous that they have been sorted into several different groups (Weiskittel et al., 2011). The suitability of different indices to predict tree growth has been compared in research (Biging and Dobbertin, 1992, Biging and Dobbertin, 1995). From these past studies it is evident that no single index has been shown to be a superior competition index in all situations, but some indices perform better with specific species in specific situations (Biging and Dobbertin, 1992, Biging and Dobbertin, 1995, Weiskittel et al., 2011). Thus comparative studies also show no clear advantage of more complex indices over simpler measures, indicating that most competition indices used in forest research are adequate (Biging and Dobbertin, 1992, Biging and Dobbertin, 1995, Weiskittel et al., 2011).

Climate change currently poses great challenges for forest research and with climate change a number of minor tree species such as Acer spp., Betulus spp., Carpinus betulus L., Tilia spp., Sorbus spp. and Robinia pseudoacacia L., which are recommended for very dry sites (Roloff and Grundmann, 2009), are receiving increasing attention. The response of trees to climate change has become an important research question and empirical research in this field has advanced considerably. Current efforts on individual tree growth modeling thus focus on including climatic effects in growth and mortality models. For example, Schmidt and Albert (2010) included mean temperature, precipitation, potential evapotranspiration and water balance during the growing season to predict site index for Picea abies and Fagus sylvatica. Nothdurft et al. (2012) modeled site index based on temperature sum and precipitation sum during the growing season. Climatic factors included in the height increment model of Kahn (1994) were mean temperature during the growing season, yearly temperature amplitude, aridity index according to DeMartonne (Martonne, 1926), precipitation during the growing season, length of growing season defined as the number of days with a mean temperature of â©¾10 Â°C. Pokharel and Froese (2009) presented a climate-sensitive basal area increment model that included the number of days during the growing season, mean annual temperature, precipitation during the growing season and annual precipitation. The mortality model presented by Nothdurft (2013) included temperature and precipitation during the growing season and soil water holding capacity.

Simultaneously, research on mixtures has made considerable progress, but mixture effects have received less attention in forest growth models than climatic effects because they are assumed to emerge from the tree specific equations parameterized from data from both pure and mixed stands. To date, mixture effects have only been explicitly implemented in the basal area increment model presented by Vospernik and Sterba (2001). The authors showed that additional variables for mixture and the interaction between mixture and competition improved the model for the three main tree species. There are, however, good reasons to assume that mixture effects might not simply emerge from individual tree equations. Empirical research shows, that in mixtures, different tree species can positively or negatively affect each other (e.g. Kelty et al., 1992). Positive effects prevail, so that on average in mixtures, there are beneficial effects (Pretzsch and SchÃ¼tze, 2009, Pretzsch et al., 2020), but results for individual plots can largely deviate from this mean (Huber et al., 2014, Pretzsch et al., 2020). The main reasons for positive mixture effects are tree specific differences in crown and root morphology (Canham et al., 1994, Kelty et al., 1992), water and nutrient use strategy (Pretzsch and SchÃ¼tze, 2009), and different leaf and litter composition (Thelina et al., 2002, Aubert et al., 2006). These differences enable two or more species to exploit the resources of a site more efficiently than a single species. Thus, these mixture effects are thought to be particularly large if species specific traits strongly contrast. For example, the mixture of Fagus sylvatica and Picea abies is highly beneficial, and gains in mixture are reported to be 21% and 37% for Picea abies and Fagus sylvatica, respectively (Pretzsch and SchÃ¼tze, 2009). Mixture gains for Quercus spp. and Pinus sylvestris are minor with 7% and 9%, respectively, because these two species have similar ecological traits (Pretzsch et al., 2020). Negative mixture effects are observed, if one tree species outcompetes the other species. For example, in mixtures of Picea abies and Abies alba Mill., positive mixture effects were only observed in 16% of the plots (Huber et al., 2014). Whether a mixture effect is positive or negative depends on age and/or size (Huber et al., 2014) and different site variables such as temperature (Huber et al., 2014), precipitation (Huber et al., 2014), aridity index (Pretzsch et al., 2020), site index (Pretzsch et al., 2020), site quality (Huber et al., 2014), slope (Huber et al., 2014), and aspect (Huber et al., 2014).

Studying the effect of the above factors of tree growth is essential for forest management and basal area increment models as part of individual tree growth simulators can also provide flexible predictions of forest growth (Weiskittel et al., 2011, p. 69). Individual tree growth simulators have been successfully applied to predict growth and yield for individual research plots (Pretzsch, 2002, Schmidt and Hansen, 2007, Vospernik et al., 2015) or to predict growth and yield for large areas (Pretzsch, 2002). Numerous researchers have simulated forest management scenarios (Vospernik and Reimoser, 2008, Engel et al., 2020) and the results have been linked to other models, e.g. wood quality (Maguire et al., 1991), habitat quality (Debeljak et al., 2001, Vospernik and Reimoser, 2008), or rockfall protection (Brauner et al., 2005).

For Austria, the individual tree growth model Prognaus has been developed (Monserud and Sterba, 1996, Monserud and Sterba, 1999, Hasenauer and Monserud, 1996, Nachtmann, 2006) from the data of the Austrian National Forest Inventory. The initial basal area increment model was estimated by Monserud and Sterba (1996) and re-parameterized by Hasenauer (2000) using simultaneous equations. Kindermann (2010) presented a climate-sensitive basal area increment model for 6 major tree species, where climatic effects were modeled by the yearly temperature sum of days above 3 Â°C and yearly precipitation. This last variant of the basal area increment model does not yet include mixture effects. Also, with climatic warming, basal area increment models for a larger number of tree species might be required. For example, Fraxinus excelsior L. and Acer pseudoplatanus L. are frequently discussed in the context of climatic warming. These two species are sufficiently represented by the Austrian National Forest Inventory, but models for them both are lacking. Furthermore, a model parameterized for Austria, could be easily be transferred to other regions in Europe and elsewhere as an evaluation study by (Engel et al., 2020).

The objective of this paper was to parameterize a basal area increment model for Austrian tree species that includes mixture and climatic effects. In addition, disturbance effects, which are already part of the basal area increment model of other individual tree growth simulators (Hasenauer, 1994, Nagel, 2009, Pretzsch and Biber, 2002), were included. Evaluation studies showed that the individual tree growth models of Prognaus reacts conservatively to thinning, underestimating the compensatory effect of the remaining trees (Vospernik et al., 2015). An additional variable for tree removal might therefore improve this behavior. All tree species with more than 200 trees observed by the Austrian National Forest Inventory, were modeled. Site factors were selected in such a way that they were as generic as possible and so that the model could be replicated in other regions.

2. Material and methods

2.1. Data

2.1.1. Forest Inventory data

For this research the plots starting from the first permanent assessment till today were used. These are the plots from the third (1981â€“1985), fourth (1986â€“1990), fifth (1992â€“1996), sixth (2000â€“2002), and seventh (2007â€“2009) Austrian National Forest Inventory (ANFI)(Forstliche Bundesversuchsanstalt, 1994), while the eighth is still in progress. The ANFI is a systematic inventory over all of Austria. ANFI clusters are located at the nodes of a 3.89 Ã— 3.89 km2 grid. Each cluster contains four sample plots, which are located at the corners of a 200 Ã— 200-m square. On each sample plot, trees with a dbh of 5 to 10.4 cm were sampled in fixed radius plots with a radius of 2.6 m, which is the critical distance for a 10.4 cm tree in angle counts (Bitterlich, 1948) with a basal area factor (BAF) of 4 m2/ha; trees with a dbh of >10.4 cm were selected by angle count sampling with BAF = 4 m2/ha. Plots, which were situated entirely in the forest and were not bisected by forest roads, were selected and the following variables were calculated: quadratic mean diameter, dominant height, basal area, crown competition factor (Krajicek et al., 1961), stand density index (Reineke, 1993), basal area of larger trees (BAL) (Wykoff, 1990), relative density, i.e. basal area of each species divided by its maximum basal area and summed up for the plot, and relative diameter, i.e. dbh related to quadratic mean diameter. Reference maximum basal area was derived from functions published by Vospernik and Sterba (2015). 22 tree species were included in the analysis and the descriptive statistics for these species are shown in Table 1.

2.1.2. Climatic data

The climatic data used for this research is the Histalp-data set (http://www.zamg.ac.at/histalp/dataset/grid/five_min.php). The histalp data set is a 5 min Ã— min grid data set that contains monthly mean temperature and monthly precipitation dating back to the year 1780 for temperature and 1801 for precipitation. The temperature data set was created by merging climate mean grids (1961â€“1990) with long-term station data (Hiebl et al., 2009). The grids of total precipitation were calculated from the monthly precipitation analysis of Efthymiadis et al. (2006) and the same grid as for the temperature data set was used. The effective coverage of the data depends on the availability of observations in the station network which progressively declines towards the early 19th century (from 192 to 5 stations) (Efthymiadis et al., 2006), but coverage is very good for the period 1981â€“2009, which was used in this analysis. The gridded temperature and precipitation data were used to calculate potential evapotranspiration according to Thornthwaiteâ€™s equation (Thornthwaite, 1948) and to calculate the following drought indices: de-Martonne index (Martonne, 1926), standard precipitation index (SPI) (McKee et al., 1993) and standardized precipitation-evapotranspiration index (SPIE) (Vicente-Serrano et al., 2010).

The de-Martonne index (dMI) is a simple index, which is calculated as dMI=PT+10, where P denotes the annual precipitation sum and T denotes the mean temperature. The SPI is the drought index that is recommended by the world meteorological organization. It is widely used, because it is comparable across regions, and permits researchers to determine the rarity of a current drought. For SPI a gamma-distribution or a Pearson-Type III distribution is fit to the climate data of a reference period. SPI is a type of z-score, i.e. the index measures the distance of the observed precipitation in terms standardized departure from the fitted distribution. Values of more than +2 or less than âˆ’2 are classified as extreme (McKee et al., 1993). Similarly, SPIE expresses the deviations of the current climatic balance (precipitationâ€“minus evapotranspiration potential) in terms of z-scores.

2.2. Statistical methods

Basal area increment was modeled with a generalized additive model (GAM). In generalized additive models, the linear predictor depends linearly on unknown smooth functions of some predictor variables, and interest focuses on inference about these smooth functions. GAMs were originally developed by Hastie and Tibshirani (1990) and blend properties of additive models with generalized linear models. A univariate response variable, Y, is related to a predictor variables and an exponential family distribution is specified for Y along with a link-function, g. For basal area increments, first a normal distribution with log-link function was specified. Functions within the GAM-framework may be specified in a parametric form or may be specified non-parametrically, simply as smooth functions. GAMs were estimated using the mgcv-package (Wood, 2011, Wood, 2017) in R (R Core Team, 2018), which implements numerous different smooth functions. After some testing, the default smooth functions, which are thin plate regression splines, were used for continuous variables, and parametric functions were used for categorical variables. Thin plate regression splines estimate the smoothing function by minimizing the least squares criterion subject to a roughness penalty based on second derivatives, i.e. if the second derivatives are zero, the function is linear and thus departures from linearity (smoothness) are penalized. Thin plate regression splines have good extrapolation properties. To test for interactions, both isotropic smooths of multiple predictors and tensor product smooths were included. Isotropic smooths are suitable for variables which all have the same units (e.g. coordinates), whereas tensor product smooths allow different flexibility in different directions and are scale invariant. The number of knots, k, specified for the smooth function determines the degree of flexibility of the smooth function. It was set to 20 for most variables, which is higher than k = 10 used as default in the mgcv-package. In some cases, however, the number of knots had to be reduced in order prevent the GAM from tracing individual data points. In terms of forest growth the model specified as(1)g(E(BAI))=Î²0+f1(Size)+f2(CompD)+f3(HDis)+f4(Clim)+Î²5(Soil)+f6(Mixt)fi are smooth functions of Size, CompD, HDis, Clim, Mixt, and Î²5 parametric coefficients of Soil. Size, CompD, HDis, Climate, Soil, Mixt stand for numerous possible variables that could be included to describe the respective growth component and mean: Tree size, competition and density, harvesting and disturbances, climate factors, soil factors, tree species mixture. Because of the multitude of possible variables available for each component in the Austrian National Forest Inventory data, modeling was carried out variable group by variable group. Within each group, predictor variables for the main effects were selected based on the lowest Akaike information criterion AIC (Akaike, 1973) and possible interactions were tested. After the variables for each group were selected, interactions between variables of different groups were tested. A quasi-distribution was finally used to account for overdispersion. Since quasi families do not have full likelihoods, gam uses the notation of extended quasi-likelihood from McCullagh and Nelder (1989).

In the GAM framework, also random effects can be easily coded. Although the benefits for incorporating such effects are undeniable, there is a major drawback. Unlike the linear counterpart, the conditional mean depends on the random effects in a non-linear fashion. Thus, while in the linear mixed-model the random effects can be set to 0 for the prediction of data sets where the random effects are unknown, this does not hold for a non-linear model and may introduce a bias in the prediction of data sets with unknown random effects (Greene, 2001, Harring and Liu, 2016). Since the model was also intended for integration in an individual tree growth model with the aim of prediction for different data, the models were parameterized without random effects. Moreover, the inclusion of random effects for major tree species is computationally very expensive. The model without random effects the parameter estimates are still unbiased, but variances may be biased and inconsistent (Lang and Laird, 1989).

3. Results

3.1. Size, density, competition, and change in competition

The raw mean values of basal area increment (Table 1) were by far the largest for Populus hybridus, but Abies alba and Salix spp. also showed large mean individual tree increments. Very low average increments were found for Alnus incana, Carpinus betulus, Sorbus spp. and Betulus spp. Basal area increment (BAI) models fitted to the data included measures for size, density, competition, harvesting, climate, soil, and tree species mixture and the final models explained 20.1%â€“61.6% of the total variation (Table 2, Table 3). Adjusted R2- values were lowest for Pinus-species and Larix decidua, whereas very large adjusted R2-values were obtained for the minor species such as Castanea sativa and Salix spp..

Modeling started with the tree size component, dbh, which is an easy variable to measure and is strongly related to basal area increment (Fig. 1). It was included in all models and BAI increased with dbh for all species. Confidence intervals were extremely small for Picea abies with 145834 trees in the data set, but wide for minor species such as Robinia pseudoacacia, Castanea sativa, Populus hybridus, and Salix spp.. As the second variable in the models, all the other variables describing size, density and competition were tested. For 10 out of 22 species the basal area of larger trees was the variable that resulted in the largest R2 and the lowest AIC, and it was variable which resulted in the lowest AIC for all major tree species. In cases where the inclusion of BAL did not result in the lowest AIC, AIC of BAL was very similar to the AIC of the competition variable with the lowest AIC. Thus, BAL was the second variable included in the model. A third variable was also tested to determine whether it was necessary to describe the size, density and competition component. Here, results were very diverse and many of the tested variables performed best for a specific species. Differences between all tested variables were minor, so that the choice seemed arbitrary. For better interpretability it was decided to retain a measure of density, complementing the measure of individual tree size and the measure of competition. The final choice was basal area per hectare, which was also the variable resulting in the lowest AIC for all major tree species. Finally, interactions among individual tree competition, tree size and stand density were tested. These interactions were only significant for a few tree species, and in many cases, these interactions described single influential points, rather than general growth patterns and were therefore discarded. This competition model proved stable during the modeling process.

BAI increment decreased with BAL for all tree species (Fig. 2). This decrease was particularly pronounced for the shade tolerant species; Abies alba, Fagus sylvatica, and Picea abies, whereas for light demanding species a much smaller decrease was observed. BAL was not significant for Tilia spp. and Populus alba and was therefore not included in the models for these species. Similarly, the growth of all tree species decreased with increasing basal area (Fig. 3), but the effect of stand density was smaller than the competition effect. Again, basal area was not significant in the models for Tilia spp. and Populus alba, but also not significant in the models for Alnus incana and Salix spp..

A variable related to tree size and competition was basal area removed during the inventory period. This variable was significant for 15 out of 22 species but could not be included for minor species or species which are not actively managed (Fig. 4) and experienced no major disturbances during the inventory periods. Models without a removal term were those for Pinus nigra, Ulmus spp., Castanea sativa, Alnus incana, Populus alba and Salix spp.. For all other tree species, removal of basal area during the survey period increased basal area increment with a greater effect for broadleaved than for coniferous species. For all species, the confidence intervals for plots with large values of basal area removed became large, indicating that such considerable removals were seldom observed in the data.

3.2. Climate

The most difficult component to include in the basal area increment models were climate effects. Due to the currently increased interest in climate change, numerous climate indices have been developed. The following climate indices were considered: deMartonne index (Martonne, 1926), the standardized precipitation index (SPI) (McKee et al., 1993) and standardized precipitation-evapotranspiration index (SPIE) (Vicente-Serrano et al., 2010). The latter two indices can be created for differing periods and periods of 1, 3, 6 and 12-month were tested. If two climate variables were used, results consistently showed the lowest AIC for models including temperature and precipitation. If a third climate variable was added, the model with potential evapotranspiration had a lower AIC than models including the dryness indices. If the dryness indices SPI and SPIE were included in the model, these two variables were almost interchangeable, with the best temporal resolution being highly variable. The best reference period for these indices was often 6 months, but also 3 months and 1 month, but never 12 months. In general, models with three climatic variables were only marginally better than models including only temperature and precipitation and so the simpler model was adopted.

Climatic variables are available at different temporal resolutions, which are monthly, quarterly, semi-annual or yearly climate values. In principle, the highest temporal resolution of climate effects resulted in the lowest AIC. However, for only a few species sufficient data were available to model climatic effects with a monthly resolution and the models partly showed biologically implausible behavior. Thus, models including climate during the growing season, defined as the period from the 1 st of April to the 30 th of September, were fit for all species.

Explanatory capacity of temperature and precipitation during the growing seasons was, however, still weak and suggested a reformulation of climatic effects into long-term mean temperature and precipitation (1960â€“2009) and positive and negative yearly deviations from the long-term mean temperature during the inventory period.

Either long-term mean temperature or long-term mean precipitation were significant in 20 of the 22 models (exceptions were Populus alba and Salix spp.) and in most cases both terms were significant. The interaction between the two variables did not improve the models and was therefore discarded. In contrast to the long-term mean, deviations from the long-term mean were only significant for major tree species with a large number of observations. All four possible deviations from the long-term mean (positive deviation in precipitation and temperature, negative deviation in precipitation and temperature) were kept in the model, if one of the four terms was significant.

Reactions to the long-term mean temperature and precipitation reflect species specific differences in warmth and moisture requirements (Fig. 5, Fig. 6). Picea abies, an ubiquitous trees species in Austria, showed little response over the wide range of observed temperatures and precipitation values, with a decrease in BAI only on very dry and warm sites and sites with overabundant precipitation, typical of high elevation forests. Similarly, the growth of Fagus sylvatica was unaffected over a wide range of temperature conditions, but this more thermophilic species showed a sharp decrease in growth when temperatures fell below 5 Â°C. Similarly, tree species of the foothill zone (e.g. Pinus nigra, Quercus spp., Alnus glutinosa), showed a clear decrease in BAI for temperatures below 10 Â°C. The tremendous increase in confidence intervals indicates the absence of these species on colder sites. Tree species of xeric sites also have extremely large confidence intervals for higher precipitation values where these species are not found. At the other end of the species range are species adapted to cold temperatures. In Austria, these are typically Larix decidua and Pinus cembra. Both species behave rather indifferently over the whole temperature range with long-term mean temperature not being significant for Pinus cembra. Both species were, however, sensitive to an increase in precipitation, which is typical of sites with long snow cover. This decrease in precipitation was more pronounced for Pinus cembra. (Fig. 7, Fig. 8, Fig. 9, Fig. 10).

Negative deviations in precipitation from the long-term mean that occurred during the inventory period did not cause large increment deviations for most species. Strongest reductions in basal area increment were observed for Pinus cembra, Quercus spp., Populus alba and Alnus glutinosa. Strong positive deviations in precipitation favored the growth of Pinus sylvestris, Quercus spp., Fraxinus excelsior, Ulmus spp. and Castanea sativa, whereas all other species behaved indifferently or showed a slight decrease. Similarly, negative temperature deviations did not strongly affect tree growth and all species behaved almost indifferently. The strongest response was observed for positive temperature deviations. Here, many species such as Picea abies, Larix decidua, Pinus nigra, Fagus sylvatica, Fraxinus excelsior, and Alnus incana showed markedly reduced growth. However, the contrary was also observed: Ulmus spp., Robinia pseudoacacia and Castanea sativa and Populus alba seemed to profit from increasing temperatures.

3.3. Soil type and soil moisture

For many species, a significant difference in tree growth on different soils was found (Fig. 11, Fig. 12, Fig. 13). Where the effect was significant, the strongest growth reduction was found on calcareous Leptosols, and the largest increase in basal area increment was observed on Planosols, on flysch, or calcareous Cambisols. Strong growth reductions were also found on moors, but the effect was not significant, because moors were rare in the data set. Coefficients for soil type were between + 0.1 and âˆ’0.1, corresponding to a 10% decrease/increase in basal area increment due to soil type. The additional effect of soil moisture (Fig. 14) had a similar magnitude. Dry and moderately-dry soils generally decreased tree growth, whereas the effect of very-moist to wet soils could be either, positive or negative, dependent on the tree species. Very moist or wet soils decreased the growth of Pinus cembra and Castanea sativa, but increased the growth of all other species, in particular, Abies alba, Populus alba, and Populus hybridus.

3.4. Mixture

Mixture was included as a relative proportion in basal area, which constrains the values between 0 and 1. For many tree species in Austria varying mixture effects were observed (Fig. 15). Mixture effects proved mainly significant when a sufficiently large number of trees was observed in the respective mixture. Notable exceptions where no significant mixture effects were observed even though a sufficiently large number of trees were available, included the mixtures of Pinus sylvestris with Picea abies and Abies alba; and Quercus spp. in mixture with Pinus sylvestris and Fagus sylvatica. Picea abies mainly benefitted from the admixture of other tree species. Significant positive mixture effects were observed in mixtures with Abies alba, Larix decidua, Pinus sylvestris, Quercus spp., Pinus cembra, Salix spp., Fraxinus excelsior, Betulus spp. and Acer spp., but in mixture with the latter three, Picea abies only benefitted in mixtures were the proportion of the admixed species was 0.5 or less. Significant negative mixture effects for Picea abies were observed in mixture with Betulus spp. and Fagus sylvatica. Similar to Picea abies, Fagus sylvatica generally benefitted from the admixture of other tree species. This species showed positive or mostly positive effects in mixture with 8 other species, which included Picea abies, Abies alba, Larix decidua, Pinus sylvestris, Carpinus betulus, Quercus spp., Fraxinus excelsior, and Acer spp.. For most other tree species positive and negative mixture effects were found and no general pattern of competitive advantages or disadvantage for these species could be discerned.

4. Discussion

4.1. Size, density, competition and harvesting

One major improvement introduced by this work was the establishment of dedicated models for numerous minor species. All these species were formerly summarized as hardwoods and softwoods, but, as the mean values show, these tree species have distinctly different growth patterns. For many of these species, the data were sufficient, to fit size, density, and competition effects; and for some, even mixture effects could be included. One drawback was that for tree species, such as Robinia pseudoacacia or Populus hybridus, data were scarce and the resulting model remained very simple. Nevertheless, the data of the Austrian National Forest Inventory in many cases were the best data source available, because for these species, experimental data or data from research experiments, is lacking.

In the new basal area increment model, the term related to size changed little but became somewhat simpler. Here, the GAM framework provided a flexible way of integrating size effects. It can adjust to any type of curve shape, and given the large amount of data, these slightly different shapes were well supported by the data. Various measures of competition were tested, but the different competition indices were almost equivalent. This finding was in line with the findings of Biging and Dobbertin (1995) who showed that differences between different competition measures for the prediction of tree growth were small.

A new variable that was included in the model was the basal area removed, which reflected the response to disturbances and harvesting and the change in competition. This proved significant in 15 out of 22 models. The new variable now facilitates the simulation of harvesting regimes, which is a major field of application of basal area increment models. Even though much effort was devoted to describing different harvesting regimes (for an overview of harvesting models see Weiskittel et al. (2011)), growth response to harvesting was only sometimes included. Here, notable exceptions are the basal area increment models of BWIN and of Silva (Nagel, 2009, Pretzsch and Biber, 2002). Nevertheless, even when a harvesting variable is included, the response to harvesting by individual tree growth models is usually underestimated (e.g. Vospernik et al., 2015). Possible reasons are a lack of extreme harvesting variants in the data (Vospernik et al., 2015) and a clear time trend in thinning response (Bevilacqua et al., 2005). Even though all trees investigated by Bevilacqua et al. (2005) showed positive harvesting reactions, it can take trees up to two years to show a positive reaction. The positive reaction to harvesting in his data was sustained for 22 years, reaching a maximum increase 9 years after harvesting (Bevilacqua et al., 2005). Thus, such distinct temporal patterns cannot be fully captured by 5-year inventory data.

4.2. Climate and Site

Recent climate simulations predict a global increase in temperature together with seasonal shifts in precipitation (Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC), IPCC (2013)). Climate warming causes tree species response to changes in temperature and precipitation at the same site. The model term representing climatic effects with long-term-mean temperature and yearly deviations from the long-term-mean temperature, was well adapted to capture and describe such effects for a given site. Moderate climate scenarios for Europe forecast an increase in temperature between 1 Â°C and 4.5 Â°C across Europe by the end of the 21st century (Jacob et al., 2014), relative to the period of 1971â€“2000. Climatic deviations observed in Austria between 1981â€“2009 for the inventory periods where an average yearly increase in temperature of 1.5 Â°C and thus, less than the 4.5 Â°C predicted in more extreme climatic scenarios but in climate simulations this may partly be compensated for by increasing long-term mean temperatures.

Growth responses to temperature and precipitation anomalies were moderate over a wide range of conditions and became more pronounced towards the species distributional limit. This is in line with findings on inter- or intra-annual growth, that focus on growth responses at the dry distribution limit (Weber et al., 2013, van der Maaten, 2012, Vospernik and Nothdurft, 2018) or at high elevation sites (Li et al., 2003, Vospernik and Nothdurft, 2018) and tree ring research is biased towards these extreme habitats (Carrer et al., 2012). Growth reductions reported in these studies for individual dry years are significant and may amount to 40â€“50% (e.g. Vospernik and Nothdurft, 2018). In a single year, during dry spells, wood formation completely stops but trees can recover quickly afterwards (van der Maaten, 2012). Such extreme years are few, and the 2â€“4-year average of positive and negative deviations observed in the forest inventory is therefore smoother and less volatile than deviations from increment cores. As a result, correlations of growth to climate are not as clear as from tree ring data from extreme sites. The short duration of such extreme events probably also explains why tree growth is better correlated with temperature and precipitation than with dryness indices. Even though the response to climate is stronger in tree ring data, a major advantage of the inventory data is that it is available across many sites and representative of different regions. In the future, there might be better ways to combine the advantages of both types of data to make use of the full information for analysis and climate predictions.

The site factors elevation, slope, and aspect originally used by Monserud and Sterba (1996) were omitted. These variables are readily available in the inventory data set, but elevation primarily represents a proxy for temperature and precipitation. The adiabatic decrease in temperature with elevation is 0.65 Â°C and through this physical relationship the two variables are linearly related, unless there are local temperature inversions. The relationship with precipitation is more diffuse, however precipitation also usually increases with elevation, but may differ between inner-alpine locations and locations at the front range Alps (Caccingia et al., 2008). Thus, the distribution of tree species and the elevation of the alpine tree line were strongly affected by climate continentality (Caccingia et al., 2008) and this was also confirmed by the model results for Larix decidua and Pinus cembra. These two species showed a decrease in growth with increasing precipitation, reflecting their sensitivity to long snow cover and snow molt infection in the case of Pinus cembra. It is also well-known that with slope and aspect, irradiation may change. Irradiation is not yet included in the model but might be added when the respective data become more readily available.

Assessing the impact of climate on tree growth requires a good knowledge of climatic, edaphic and synecological controls acting upon each individual tree species. Soil type and/or soil moisture is often included in growth models (e.g. Monserud and Sterba, 1996, Schmidt and Albert, 2010, Pretzsch and Biber, 2002), and proved significant also in this modeling approach. Probably the largest differences in tree growth were caused by the parent material of soils. Calcareous Leptosols, which are poor in nutrients and have a low water-holding capacity showed the strongest negative impact on basal area increment. Most likely these soils are also classified as dry, so that effects for soil type and soil moisture taken together result in an even stronger decreases than would be inferred from the soil type itself. Here, the causal variables were soil water holding capacity and nutrient availability. These variables are for example included in the site index model of Schmidt and Albert (2010). If this information becomes available for the data from the Austrian National Forest Inventory, the inclusion of these variables might further refine the basal area increment model in the future.

The aim of this research was to develop a simple and transferable model and variables were therefore restricted to those, which are readily available for different data sets. Thus, variables such as growth district, vegetation type, or the thickness of F-humus and H-humus, that were included by Monserud and Sterba (1996) were also omitted. This may result in lower R2-values but facilitates the application of the model and permits an application of the model outside Austria in Central Europe, where similar tree species occur, and comparable climatic conditions exist.

4.3. Mixture

Management of mixed woods is advocated as an effective adaptation strategy to increase ecosystem resilience in the context of climate change. Including both mixture and climate effects in the basal area increment model enables evaluation of these effects in tree growth simulations. Different tree species can facilitate or compete with each other (Kelty et al., 1992) and mixture effects can be both positive and negative (Kelty et al., 1992), but positive mixture effects prevail (Pretzsch and SchÃ¼tze, 2009). Mixture effects arise from a complementary resource use of different tree species due to differences in crown (Kelty et al., 1992, Pretzsch and SchÃ¼tze, 2009, Pretzsch, 2014) and root morphology (Kelty et al., 1992, Schmid and Kazda, 2002) and the resulting light use (Pretzsch, 2014) and water and nutrient (Thelina et al., 2002) uptake. In addition, mixture effects have also been also reported to originate from the fact that different tree species influence soil water conditions (Schume et al., 2002) and humus formation (Aubert et al., 2006) in different ways. According to ecological niche theory, mixture effects are particularly strong for tree species, which are highly complementary. Large gains in increment are reported for combining light-demanding with shade-tolerant (ZÃ¶hrer, 1969) and shallow with deep-rooting species (Schmid and Kazda, 2002), or slim crowned-tree species with more lateral species (Pretzsch and SchÃ¼tze, 2009). Gains in such mixtures can amount to 30%, whereas the benefit from mixing more similar tree species, e.g. Quercus spp.-Pinus sylvestris is only 7% or 9% (Pretzsch et al., 2020).

The results from our modeling effort confirmed the ecological niche theory in that the mixtures of species with similar traits did not significantly alter growth, even though the number of observations in the data set were large. In diverse mixtures, at individual tree level either one of the two species gained at the expense of the other species or both species seemed to benefit. An example of the first pattern is the mixture of Picea abies and Fagus sylvatica. The individual tree growth of Fagus sylvatica increased with the admixture of Picea abies, whereas the opposite was true for Picea abies, which responded with decreased individual tree growth. This pattern corroborated studies on the individual tree growth of these two species, where the growth of Picea abies was more strongly reduced in mixture than growth of Fagus sylvatica (Nothdurft and Engel, 2020), but at the stand level the net effect was often positive for this well studied mixture, possibly also due to differences in packing density for these two species (Pretzsch and SchÃ¼tze, 2009). The latter pattern, with positive effects for both tree species, was observed for Larix decidua and Picea abies. Here, the mixture was positive for both species at the individual tree level, confirming the results of ZÃ¶hrer (1969). From the inventory data, mixture effects for rare species were also derived. To the best of our knowledge, mixture effects for Sorbus spp. have not been investigated before. This study could confirm mixture effects for Fraxinus excelsior, Fagus sylvatica, Picea abies and Quercus spp..

Almost all the mixture effects found, varied with species proportion. This is in line with findings from (e.g. Huber et al., 2014). Other mixture effects frequently reported variations with stand age, density, and site (Pretzsch and SchÃ¼tze, 2009, Huber et al., 2014). This was not confirmed in this modeling approach, even though the respective interactions were introduced in the models. This is partly due to too few observations to fit such effects even from a large inventory data set, and partly due to too large a number of confounding variables in the data set. With the addition of interactions, the very flexible GAM-framework seemed to trace smaller patterns in the data rather than general growth patterns.

5. Conclusions

The model predicted basal area increment based on size, competition, density, climate, harvesting and disturbances, edaphic factors, and mixture effects and was therefore based on important tree growth factors. In the model approach, proxy-variables were avoided and instead the causal variables were integrated, whenever possible in order to describe general growth patterns rather than particularities of the data. The most difficult component to include in the basal area increment model was the site component, since this term summarizes a multitude of environmental factors. Moreover, the large number of possible site factors made it difficult to find a reasonable model that is adequate for all sites represented by the entire forest inventory. Limiting factors for growth may differ between sites, and regional models for tree growth might be needed. In particular, little is still known about tree growth responses on non-extreme sites, which represent the majority of forest sites. Novel in this study is the inclusion of climatic effects as long-term means, representing the site component of climate, and deviations thereof representing weather conditions and/or climatic change. This approach is a step forward in understanding the climate-growth relationship in inventory data, but probably even better models can be found in the future, since yearly or daily increment data show better correlations of climate and growth. This is because this type of data has a better temporal resolution but does not usually encompass a multitude of sites necessary for inferences that include large areas. Thus it might be possible to obtain better models by combining the two types of data, and model distinct temporal growth patterns from year-ring data, while at the same time preserving the advantages of a large statistical data set which assures robust mean predictions. The same may apply to disturbances, which also have distinct temporal patterns. The new modeling approach is better adapted to the simulation of tree growth response to climate change and to mitigating mixture effects, since both effects are explicitly integrated in the model. Generalized additive models provide very flexible tools for growth modeling, with great potential for modelling complex relationships, but additional care has to be taken to avoid model overfitting.
